OESD Food Service Update:

Starting September 1st, the USDA has extended several of the Summer Food program waivers to allow us to feed all students free meals (breakfast and lunch) until December 31st or until funding is unavailable.

Student breakfast and lunch will be free until further notice! Students must take a complete meal. Parents do not need to make any change to student accounts.

More information will be coming from Mrs. Krott.

See link for an update on the status of spectators at fall sporting events.

As it stands right now, this is what we have to plan for:
Volleyball: Players + Coaches + Game Personnel = 25

We will keep parents updated on our planning. A Zoom Fall Sports Parent meeting will be planned for September 10. We will be watching the legislation described in the link.

The first step requires our school board to update our Athletic Safety Plan so that spectators can be permitted.

A message from our Cafeteria:

We are asking HIGH SCHOOL students to download and set up a SchoolCafe account, in their name, in order to make check out quicker and more efficient. The student will then have their own log in. Parents will still be the only one with credit card information and restriction privileges on the account.

If you do not feel comfortable with this, parents may use their personal account and students can take a clear, close up picture of the barcode with their phone. Students will also be able to use their student ID once we have Picture Day and the IDs are made.

Thank you for your help in our ever changing days.

Impact Teen Drivers is a national traffic safety education nonprofit whose mission is to save lives by fighting reckless and distracted driving (with a focus on teens and their influencers).

Impact Teen Drivers (ITD) has been "Zooming," putting on webinars and creating online learning opportunities for teens and their influencers. Parents and teens can participate in this evidence-based program.

Remember, it doesn’t matter whether you are the driver or passenger—WE ALL contribute to a safe ride.

Click on link below to register for our webinar Monday, July 20th at 1 p.m. EDT:
https://us02web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_YyZWWLYISNSk0QOa8IMj3g

To all incoming 7th-12th grade students,

The OEHS weightroom will be open for use Monday through Thursday starting June 22 through August 6 from 8am-10am.

See attached for guidelines that must be followed. Mrs. Francis (kfrancis@ottoeldred.org) will oversee the weightroom activities. Students will need to sign up for a preferred session (40 min) to use the indoor facilities. We will plan to schedule siblings/relatives together. Prior to your session or following, additional workout activities may be done on the track area or in the gym (when available). Your session will be consistent daily through August 6. Only your weightroom time will be limited to 40 minutes.

BB-VB Open Gym / FB Skills Sessions will begin July 1. Schedule TBA.

By attending these sessions, you agree to abide by the guidelines in place.

post_text:
Sheetz, a major restaurant and convenience chain across the Mid-Atlantic, announced the expansion of the Kidz Meal Bagz program providing free food to help children and families in need as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. Meal Bagz are now be available at all 600 Sheetz locations and will be available all day, while supplies last. The Meal Bagz include a turkey sandwich, chips and a drink.

Families interested in taking advantage of the free Kidz Meal Bagz program can go to any Sheetz location and ask an employee for a meal at the register or through the drive-through. Meals will be available daily while supplies last. Families will be offered one bag per child.

The program will be available for the next two weeks at which time it will be reevaluated based on community need.

post_text:
Meal Delivery Update:
2025 meal deliveries were made this week in just 4 days!

Those meals required over 40 hours of labor from a wonderful group of ladies, which then needed 30 hours of delivery time (by a fantastic set of drivers) over hundreds of miles of road requiring dozens of gallons of gasoline.

That is about 250 gallons of milk consumed this week, which came from dozens of cows (even some chocolate ones), raised by PA farmers.

Each meal contained an entrée for lunch and breakfast, with multiple fruits and multiple vegetables which were all grown/raised/packaged and delivered by our fellow Americans.

These meals not only keep our kids "full", at least for a few minutes anyway, but also keep our local, state and national economy moving. Our producers need to be needed!

If you have not signed up for meal delivery yet, please call and get signed up!

#oesdmatters
#Meals4KidsinPA

PA Department of Education (PDE) announced today all schools in the commonwealth will remain closed through at least April 6 as a result of the COVID-19 response efforts. The closure order could be extended beyond April 6 if necessary to save lives and stop the spread of COVID-19.

PDE has also cancelled standardized testing for students in career and technical education (CTE) programs for the 2019-20 school year. These include exams from the National Occupational Competency Testing Institute (NOCTI) and National Institute of Metalworking Skills (NIMS).

post_text:
Tonight, March 17th was our Otto-Eldred Elementary's Computer Science & STEM Fair.

Students worked extremely hard to create contraptions for our student competition. PreK-1st grade were welcome to make Leprechaun Traps. 2nd and 3rd grade built bridges to hold a mug of gold. 4th-6th grade built contraptions that could hold a mug of gold!!!

Although we are not able to enjoy this evening in person, we wanted to show off our student work. Thanks to all students who participated!!

Happy St. Patrick's Day!!

post_text:
Otto-Eldred SD Student Meal Service:

The Otto-Eldred Schools will be providing free breakfast and lunch on weekdays during the school closure. People living close by may pick up a Grab and Go bag at the Elementary or High School main doors, in the bus circle between 9 and 10am starting Tuesday March 17th. All students that are normally bussed will have a Grab and Go bag delivered to their bus stop approximately two hours after the normal bus pick up time. Parents or students are asked to wait at the bus stop to receive the meals. All children age birth through 12th grade may receive meals.
Please notify the school if you would like to decline meals or if you have children in the home that have not entered school yet. Chris Krott ckrott@ottoeldred.org or 814-817-1391 or the Main Office at 814-817-1380
Thank you for your patience as we work through these unusual circumstances and new routine.

Chris Krott, Food Service Director
Matthew Splain, Superintendent

post_text:
Pennsylvania Department of Education is in the process of examining the PA Science Standards. PDE has offered a series of stakeholder engagement sessions and on Thursday some of our Otto-Eldred High School students and staff attended a session. Student voices were heard when they advocated for quality science education, quality experiences and equitable opportunities in our region.

These students were well-spoken and captivated a roomful of educators, state representatives, etc. O-E students matter and these students made that known!!

post_text:
Dear Elementary Parents / Guardians,

We have been in close contact with the Eldred Borough regarding the needed sewer line repairs under Main Street. Due to the continued issues seen over the past week, the repair on the line will occur sooner than anticipated. The Borough has been monitoring the line over the last week and will continue to do so during the upcoming week. To help reduce any additional issues, we will minimize water use during the day.

Activities to repair the sewer line will begin after school on Friday, February 21 and should be completed by end of day on Sunday, February 23. The elementary building will be closed for any use from Friday after school through Sunday. If we anticipate any issue opening the building as normal on Monday, February 24, notice will be sent on Sunday.

Please call the District Office at 817-1380, option 3 with any questions.
